# /sparkrun:tune

Tune Triton fused MoE kernels for optimal inference performance.

## Usage

```
/sparkrun:tune <runtime> <recipe> [options]
```

## Examples

```
/sparkrun:tune sglang qwen3.5-35b-bf16-sglang -H 192.168.11.13
/sparkrun:tune vllm qwen3-moe-vllm --cluster mylab --tp 4
/sparkrun:tune sglang my-recipe -H myhost --tp 1 --tp 2 --tp 4
/sparkrun:tune vllm my-recipe -H myhost --parallel 2
```

## Behavior

When this command is invoked:

1. Determine the runtime (sglang or vllm) and recipe.
2. Run kernel tuning:

```bash
# SGLang tuning
sparkrun tune sglang <recipe> --hosts <ip> [--tp 1 --tp 2 --tp 4]

# vLLM tuning
sparkrun tune vllm <recipe> --hosts <ip> [--tp 1 --tp 2 --tp 4]
```

3. Tuning runs on a single host inside the recipe's container. It generates optimal Triton tile configs (BLOCK_M/N/K, warps, stages) for each TP size.
4. Results are saved to the sparkrun cache and automatically mounted in future inference runs.

## Common Options

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `--hosts, -H` | Target host (uses first host only) |
| `--cluster` | Use a saved cluster (uses first host) |
| `--tp N` | TP size(s) to tune (repeatable; default: 1,2,4,8) |
| `--image` | Override container image |
| `--output-dir` | Override tuning config output directory |
| `--parallel N` | Run N tuning jobs concurrently (default: 1) |
| `--skip-clone` | Skip cloning runtime repo (scripts already in image) |
| `--dry-run` | Show what would be done |

## Notes

- Tuning only runs on a single host — multi-host clusters use the first host
- Results are cached and auto-mounted in future `sparkrun run` commands for the same model
- Use `--parallel` to speed up tuning by running multiple TP sizes concurrently
- Tuning configs can also be synced from registries (sparkrun does this automatically during `run`)
